__data__.text: Nagaenthran a/l K. Dharmalingam was born on 13 September 1988 in Ipoh, Malaysia.
Nagaenthran was the second of four children, having an elder sister named Sharmila and two younger brothers, one of whom is named Navinkumar.
Nagaenthran's father passed away during Nagaenthran's death row imprisonment in Singapore.
Nagaenthran's mother, Panchalai Supermaniam, often went out for work and entrusted Nagaenthran and his siblings to the care of their grandmother and relatives during his childhood.
Nagaenthran completed his five-year secondary school education at the age of 17.
Nagaenthran worked at a factory after finishing his secondary school education.
Nagaenthran decided to go to Singapore to find employment against the wishes of his family, especially his mother.
Nagaenthran found a job as a security guard in Singapore.
Nagaenthran visited his family in Ipoh regularly.
Nagaenthran last returned to Malaysia and visited his family in 2008 during Deepavali.
On 22 April 2009, Nagaenthran was arrested by Central Narcotics Bureau (CNB) officers when he was traveling from Malaysia to Singapore through the Woodlands Checkpoint.
During a search of Nagaenthran and his belongings, the police discovered a bundle strapped to Nagaenthran's thigh, and the bundle contained a total amount of 42.72 g of diamorphine (pure heroin).
A friend and traveling partner of Nagaenthran, named Kumarsen, was also arrested but later released.
Nagaenthran admitted to his interrogators that he knew he was carrying drugs.
Nagaenthran claimed that he needed money to pay off his debts and his father's heart surgery fees, which was why he committed the crime.
Nagaenthran later retracted his confession and denied having knowledge of the contents of the bundle of drugs found on him.

In January 2013, new amendments took effect in Singapore that allowed judges to sentence drug traffickers to life imprisonment with caning not less than 15 strokes instead of death, if they were merely couriers and met certain conditions.

The conditions for receiving a life sentence include receiving a certificate of substantive assistance from the public prosecutor for helping narcotics police disrupt drug trafficking activities or having diminished responsibility due to mental illness.
Nagaenthran applied for re-sentencing in January 2013 due to clinical intellectual disability and mental illness.
Nagaenthran's case was reviewed by the original trial judge, Chan Seng Onn, in the High Court.
A psychiatric report concluded that Nagaenthran did not have clinical intellectual disability or mental illness.
Nagaenthran did not receive a certificate of substantive assistance from the Central Narcotics Bureau (CNB).
Nagaenthran requested mercy in 2015 based on intellectual disability, low IQ, impaired executive functioning, and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder.
The High Court dismissed Nagaenthran's re-sentencing application in 2017.
Four psychiatric and psychological experts, including one called by the defense, agreed that Nagaenthran was not intellectually disabled.
Nagaenthran showed inconsistencies in his account of his education qualifications.
The High Court found that Nagaenthran was capable of manipulation and evasion.
Nagaenthran tried to dissuade CNB officers from searching him by stating that he was "working in security".
The High Court dismissed another appeal of Nagaenthran's case in 2018.
Nagaenthran, through his lawyer Eugene Thuraisingam, filed two separate appeals to the Court of Appeal to commute his sentence under the newly enacted death penalty laws.
The five-judge Court of Appeal dismissed both appeals on 27 May 2019.

Nagaenthran Dharmalingam was sentenced to death for drug trafficking.
Nagaenthran had the intention of paying off some of his debts with his actions.
Nagaenthran's actions were deliberate, calculated, and purposeful.
Nagaenthran was found to have a "criminal mind" and was able to weigh benefits and risks, and the concept of right or wrong.
Nagaenthran lost his final bid to be re-sentenced.
Nagaenthran appealed to the President of Singapore Halimah Yacob for clemency.
Nagaenthran's clemency petition was rejected on 1 June 2020, finalizing his death sentence.
The last time clemency was granted in Singapore was in 1998.
In 1998, 19-year-old Mathavakannan Kalimuthu was pardoned from execution for murder.
Mathavakannan was paroled and released in 2012 after serving 16 years of his life sentence due to good behavior.
Nagaenthran's case attracted international attention while he was appealing for clemency.
Many opposed the death penalty and asked Singapore to spare Nagaenthran's life.
Nagaenthran's mother Panchalai Supermaniam (aged 57 in 2019) and family joined in the efforts to plead for mercy.
Malaysian human rights lawyer N Surendran denounced Singapore for unfairly subjecting a mentally disabled man to a death sentence.
N Surendran, together with Nagaenthran's new lawyer M Ravi, argued that there was no fair trial for Nagaenthran.
They claimed that Nagaenthran's defence's psychiatric evidence was not fully considered compared to the reports of the prosecution's psychiatrists.
Singapore's law minister K Shanmugam argued that there is no inequality in treating foreigners and locals under the law for drug trafficking.

Malaysian lawyers and both international and local anti-death penalty activists, including World Coalition Against the Death Penalty, Human Rights Watch, Amnesty International, United Nations Commission on Human Rights, and FIDH, tried to appeal to the Singapore government for clemency for Nagaenthran Dharmalingam.
Nagaenthran Dharmalingam was sentenced to death in Singapore for drug trafficking.
Nagaenthran Dharmalingam is a Malaysian citizen.
Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's lawyers and anti-death penalty activists reiterated that Nagaenthran Dharmalingam was mentally disabled and should not be hanged for his crime.
Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's lawyers and anti-death penalty activists insisted on Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's innocence.
An online petition was made to plead to President Halimah Yacob of Singapore to spare Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's life.
The online petition garnered more than 102,000 signatures.
There is an intention to bring forward the matter to the International Court of Justice (ICJ) against Singapore for not conforming with the international norms to not practice the death penalty.
There are concerns that Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's execution might violate international human rights and law, which rules that any mentally unfit capital offenders should not be executed.
In the United States, Divisions of Social Justice of the American Psychiatric Association (APA) called Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's case a "flagrant breach" of human rights.
Human rights groups repeatedly called for Singapore to abolish the death penalty.
Public figures like Singaporean rapper-musician Subhas Nair and British billionaire Richard Branson asked for Singapore to show mercy on Nagaenthran Dharmalingam.
More than 200 friends and family members of other death row convicts asked for Singapore to spare Nagaenthran Dharmalingam's life.

Deepavali is an annual Hindu festival.
Nagaenthran and his family celebrate Deepavali annually.
The execution date of Nagaenthran was six days after Deepavali.
Nagaenthran's family could not celebrate Deepavali due to his execution date.
A man was arrested on 4 November 2021 for posting a poster advocating against Nagaenthran's death sentence at a train in Kuala Lumpur.
The act of posting the poster was classified as an illegal act of public provocation.
The Ministry of Home Affairs (MHA) released a statement regarding Nagaenthran's case.
Nagaenthran was accorded full due process under the law.
Nagaenthran was represented by legal counsel throughout his case.
Nagaenthran did not commit the act under duress.
Nagaenthran was not substantially mentally impaired to the extent of being ineligible for execution.
Nagaenthran clearly understood the magnitude of his actions.
There was no necessity to review Nagaenthran's case.
Nagaenthran's avenues of appeal were all exhausted.
The amount of heroin Nagaenthran trafficked in Singapore is equivalent to about 3,560 straws of heroin.
The amount of heroin Nagaenthran trafficked is sufficient to feed the addiction of about 510 abusers for a week.
Singapore has one of the lowest crime rates globally due to the death penalty.
The death penalty is necessary to clamp down on drug crimes.
The penalties for illegal trafficking, importation or exportation of drugs are made clear at Singapore's borders.
The Singapore authorities have set execution dates ahead for some other death row inmates.
Malaysian lawyer Mahajoth Singh launched a one-man protest against the execution of Nagaenthran.
Malaysian lawyer N Surendran asked for mercy on Nagaenthran's life.

Nagaenthran's mental age being below 18 years old is not supported by medical basis.
Lawyer M Ravi, who has no medical expertise, claimed that Nagaenthran's mental age is below 18 years old.
M Ravi met Nagaenthran once and interacted with him for 26 minutes, six days before the appeal hearing.
Justice See was not convinced by M Ravi's arguments regarding international law violations due to capital punishment.
Justice See stated that there is no legal basis for international law to take precedence over domestic law.
Nagaenthran's appeal hearing was concluded by Justice See with the statement that the law should take its course.
Nagaenthran had already been accorded full due process and exhausted his appeals.
An appeal to the Court of Appeal was heard on 9 November 2021.
The rushed schedule to close up on Nagaenthran's last-minute appeal process was criticized by lawyer N. Surendran as a denial of due legal process for Nagaenthran.
Testimonies of prison officers who knew Nagaenthran were presented in court and disputed the supposed mentally ill behavior of Nagaenthran.
A senior prison officer who had befriended Nagaenthran for the past three years had not seen any abnormal behavior from Nagaenthran.
Nagaenthran was able to request religious counselling after being told that he would be hanged in the near future.
Another prison officer said Nagaenthran had no problem communicating with the prison officers in English, Malay and Tamil.
Nagaenthran was able to make requests and respond to instructions.
Nagaenthran asked for religious counselling and a DVD player to play religious songs.
Nagaenthran was also able to request for phone calls to his family members and for them to visit him.
Nagaenthran was able to select whichever prison officers who could help fulfill his needs during the final days prior to his execution.

Nagaenthran and people he interacted with were isolated to avoid spreading infection to more people and be given medical treatment in the meantime.
As of 12 November 2021, 54 supervising prison officers and a total of 169 prisoners from the prison, including those on death row, were confirmed to be infected with COVID-19.
Many human rights groups pushed for the abolition of the death penalty in Malaysia.
Most Malaysians believed that the death penalty should remain for serious crimes like murder and certain offences of corruption other than drug trafficking.
Support for the death penalty remains high in Malaysia despite the decreasing numbers of new death sentences given by the courts.

Legal professionals and enforcement, including some lawyers and police officers, commented that there should be some powers of discretion given to the judges to impose life imprisonment in some capital cases instead of death with respect to its mitigating circumstances.
They generally felt that the death penalty is overall still relevant to use against drug trafficking and murder and other offences.
Datuk Seri Nazri Abdul Aziz hoped that Malaysia can review its death penalty laws for drug traffickers in Malaysia.
Singapore's representative to the UN and Ambassador Umej Bhatia responded to the UN's pressure to pardon Nagaenthran.
The courts in Singapore have already made it clear in their verdicts that Nagaenthran may have borderline intellectual functioning but he did not have mild intellectual disability.
The courts gave strictest due consideration to determine the eligibility of Nagaenthran's condition for execution.
Nagaenthran's personal psychiatrist has also agreed that the Malaysian had no intellectual disability.
There is no international consensus on the death penalty or what is the threshold of "serious crimes".
Every country has the sovereign right to decide on its use of the death penalty and the types of capital offences they defined under the law.
The prosecution's decisions are independent of the government and they are still liable for review of their decisions.
Nagaenthran has already appealed for reviewing the prosecution's decisions before the courts found no error.
Malaysia's human rights lawyer N. Surendran and Lawyers for Liberty claimed that the Singapore government was fabricating their stand that Nagaenthran was accorded full due process.

The courts had not given Nagaenthran a full due court process by not taking into consideration of his intellectual and mental impairment or making accommodation to address them during the court proceedings.
Human Rights Watch's senior disability rights expert Emina Ćerimović commented on Nagaenthran's case, stating that the inhumanity shown by the Singaporean authorities is truly shocking.
The government's determination to execute a man with an intellectual disability for importing a small amount of drugs is disproportionate and cruel, and deserves global condemnation.

The Malaysian Bar, together with the Advocates Association of Sarawak and the Sabah Law Society, appealed to the Singapore government for clemency to lower Nagaenthran's death sentence to life imprisonment.

They cited that they maintain their respect for Singapore's laws but implored the city-state, on the basis of compassion and humanity, to assess Nagaenthran's mental state to see if he is mentally competent to be hanged.
Nagaenthran's family and lawyer M Ravi expressed that they will sue Singapore's attorney general Lucien Wong for negligence and willful disregard of human life by the judicial system.

Wong sent a letter to Ravi, stating that Ravi's other allegations against the legal system in Nagaenthran's case amounted to "contempt of court" and he should retract them and apologise by a deadline of 22 November.
Ravi has stated that he will not retract his statements or apologise to the attorney general.
Yang di-Pertuan Agong from Malaysia wrote to the President of Singapore, hoping that clemency could be given to Nagaenthran.

The President of Singapore Halimah Yacob replied to the Agong's clemency letter, firmly stating that Nagaenthran was being 'accorded full due process under the law' and thus refused to grant clemency to Nagaenthran.
On 24 January 2022, Netto sought an adjournment of the appeal for Nagaenthran's case, and it was granted by the courts.
The appeal was eventually heard on 1 March 2022.
During the appeal, Netto argued for Nagaenthran to be subjected to a psychiatric assessment prior to his execution.
Netto tried to admit the reports of two foreign psychologists as evidence to support Nagaenthran's case.
The judges stated that the last-minute drip-feeding of evidence was tantamount to an abuse of the court process.
Deputy Public Prosecutor Wong Woon Kwong described the appeal as a "continuation of a very cynical attempt to abuse the process of the court".
Wong criticized Netto for seeking to suppress the prison's independent medical records.
The judgement was reserved, and while awaiting the verdict, rights groups continually sought clemency for Nagaenthran.
Four weeks later, on 29 March 2022, the five-judge Court of Appeal dismissed the appeal.
The court issued harsh words of condemnation and criticism towards Netto and M. Ravi for abusing the court process.
Chief Justice Sundaresh Menon pointed out that the appeal was filed based on inadmissible evidence.

Menon criticized Ravi's speculation that Nagaenthran has a mental age below 18 years old, stating that there was no evidence to show any deterioration of Nagaenthran's mental faculties during his 13-year stay on Changi Prison's death row.
The court accepted that Nagaenthran possessed borderline intellectual functioning but not mild intellectual disability.
The two foreign psychologists' evidence was rejected as they did not personally assess Nagaenthran.
The Attorney-General's Chambers had intended to enter psychiatric and medical reports from check-ups done on Nagaenthran in 2021 as evidence in court.

Lawyers for Liberty (LFL) accused the Singapore government of violating international law.
LFL claimed that Singapore failed to abide by the conditions of prohibiting the killing of intellectually disabled persons by sentencing Nagaenthran to death.
M Ravi, together with LFL, asked the Malaysian government to bring forward Nagaenthran's case to the International Court of Justice (ICJ).
The Global Commission on Drug Policy stated that the death penalty was an inappropriate response to any offences, including drug-related crimes, citing Nagaenthran's case.
A protest was made on 3 April 2022 at Hong Lim Park against the government's use of the death penalty in light of Nagaenthran's failed appeal.

The ASEAN Intergovernmental Commission on Human Rights (AICHR) was urged to intervene in Nagaenthran's case and other death penalty issues from Singapore, as well as advocate for the abolition of the death penalty in the ASEAN member nations.
Some netizens agreed with and supported the judges' standing that Nagaenthran should face execution for his crime.
In a 2021 survey, more than 80% of Singaporeans believed that the death penalty should remain in Singapore due to its deterrent effect and relevance in fighting crime.
Nagaenthran's lawyer, M Ravi, expressed his support for Nagaenthran's life to be spared.
The execution of Abdul Kahar bin Othman, a Singaporean drug convict, took place at dawn on 30 March 2022.
Abdul Kahar's execution was the first to be carried out in Singapore during the COVID-19 pandemic.
A second clemency appeal submitted by Nagaenthran's family and supporters was rejected by the President of Singapore on 31 March 2022.
Nagaenthran's death sentence was upheld by the dismissal of his second clemency plea.

Kokila Annamalai, a rights activist, planned to organize a candlelight vigil for Nagaenthran at Hong Lim Park on 25 April 2022.
Nagaenthran's family, including his three siblings, intended to travel to Singapore to visit him in Changi Prison.
British billionaire Richard Branson and British actor Stephen Fry made appeals on social media for Nagaenthran's sentence to be commuted.
In his appeal, Branson described the death penalty as a "horrible blotch" on Singapore's reputation.
Human rights groups requested that Singapore transfer Nagaenthran to a Malaysian prison through a prisoner exchange program.
Protests against Nagaenthran's execution intensified as the death warrant for another Malaysian drug convict, Datchinamurthy Kataiah, was finalized.
Datchinamurthy's execution was scheduled for 29 April 2022, two days after Nagaenthran's execution date.
The vigil was held as scheduled, with several public figures, including rapper Subhas Nair, opposition politician Paul Tambyah, and writer Alfian Sa'at, in attendance.
Some Singaporeans joined the vigil out of sympathy for Nagaenthran and Datchinamurthy, while others wanted to learn more about the death penalty in Singapore.
Nagaenthran's family could not attend the vigil due to a law prohibiting foreigners from participating in local protests.
Nagaenthran's cousin, Thenmoli Sunniah, spoke on behalf of the family and stated that they would not give up hope for Nagaenthran's case.
Datchinamurthy's family attended the vigil to show support for Nagaenthran's family and protest the executions.
Nagaenthran and Datchinamurthy were close friends who shared neighboring cells at the death row section of Changi Prison.
Both men's mothers bonded due to their shared loss and common goal of saving their sons from execution.

On 25 April 2022, Nagaenthran's mother, Panchalai Supermaniam, filed a lawsuit against Sundaresh Menon, the Chief Justice of Singapore.
Panchalai filed the lawsuit without a lawyer, as no lawyers in Singapore were willing to represent her due to fear of reprisals from the court.
The lawsuit alleges that Menon, as the former attorney general, had prosecuted Nagaenthran and secured his conviction, which Panchalai claims deprived her son's rights to a fair trial.
The lawsuit was set to be heard on 26 April 2022, the day before Nagaenthran's execution.
The Court of Appeal dismissed Panchalai's lawsuit on 26 April 2022.
The three-judge panel, consisting of Belinda Ang, Andrew Phang, and Judith Prakash, found the application to be "devoid of merit".
Justice Phang described the application as baseless and an attempt to prolong matters without merit.
Nagaenthran did not raise the allegation in his previous appeal the month before.
Deputy Public Prosecutor (DPP) Wong Woon Kwong criticized Panchalai for filing a meritless lawsuit.
CJ Menon was not involved in any of the decisions pertaining to Nagaenthran's prosecution.
DPP Wong urged the court to compel Panchalai to disclose the identities of those who played a part in submitting the lawsuit.
After the dismissal of the lawsuit, Nagaenthran made a final request to spend time with his family members in the Supreme Court building.
Nagaenthran was given permission to hold his family members' hands one final time.
A small vigil was held by activists in Malaysia on the night before Nagaenthran's execution.
Fifty people attended the event.
Two Malaysian lawyers were being probed by the police for taking part in the vigil.

Nagaenthran was executed at Changi Prison in Singapore on 27 April 2022, at around dawn, after being arrested for drug trafficking 13 years ago.
Abdul Kahar Othman was the first person to be executed in Singapore after the end of a two-year moratorium due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
Nagaenthran was the fifth Malaysian drug trafficker to be hanged in Singapore since 2016.
Nagaenthran's family, including his 22-year-old brother Navinkumar and 36-year-old sister Sharmila, planned to collect his body and take it back to their hometown in Ipoh for funeral preparations.
The family was saddened and shocked at their loss and were dissatisfied with Nagaenthran's final sentence, although they had come to terms with his death.
The funeral was expected to be held on 29 April 2022, two days after Nagaenthran's execution.
A wake was conducted for Nagaenthran in Singapore before the body was brought back to Malaysia, with over a hundred people attending it.
Nagaenthran's sister revealed that after the funeral, Nagaenthran's remains would be laid to rest in a Hindu cemetery in Buntong, Ipoh.
Over 200 family members and friends were present at the funeral.
Sharmila did not allow any politicians to attend the funeral, claiming they were coming only for publicity but did not offer assistance while Nagaenthran was on death row.
In the year 2022, a total of eleven executions, including Nagaenthran's, were officially carried out in Singapore, all for drug trafficking.
Reprieve's director Maya Foa criticized Nagaenthran's execution and described him as a "victim of a tragic miscarriage of justice".
M Ravi offered his condolences to Nagaenthran's family and said he would continue to fight for the abolition of the death penalty in Singapore.

McMahon, an individual, stated that he felt the death penalty was ineffective in preventing drug trafficking.
McMahon added that it was shocking to see the death penalty being put into use for relatively "non-serious" crimes like drug trafficking.
Another individual, Morry Bailes, was critical of the use of the death penalty by Singapore and Japan in light of Nagaenthran's execution by Singapore for drug trafficking.
Bailes stated that the claims of the death penalty as an effective deterrent were greatly contradicted by the experience of many other countries.
Bailes stated that hanging a mere drug mule like Nagaenthran would not be able to achieve the ends of justice.
Bailes stated that witnesses, juries, and courts make mistakes, but the death penalty, once carried out, is irreversible.
The case of Nagaenthran's execution brought attention to the cases of the nine remaining Malaysians on Singapore's death row.
The United Nations criticized Singapore for executing Nagaenthran and Abdul Kahar Othman.
The United Nations stated that Singapore should impose a moratorium as a first step to abolish the death penalty.
The United Nations urged Singapore to not execute Datchinamurthy Kataiah, who was the third drug trafficker facing imminent execution in Singapore.
On the same day Nagaenthran was executed, the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) made an official statement.
The AGC strongly condemned the allegations and rumors spread in relation to Nagaenthran's case.
The AGC specifically mentioned to Nagaenthran's counsel about Chief Justice Sundaresh Menon's appointment as the Attorney General during the prosecution of Nagaenthran.
Nagaenthran himself, under his lawyer's advice, made no objections for Menon to preside the lawsuit.
Nagaenthran's mother filed a lawsuit with the help of friends and activists.
The organizations of legal papers clearly were not solely the work of Nagaenthran's mother.
The Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) of Singapore considered the allegations against the handling of Nagaenthran K. Dharmalingam's case as contempt of court.
The AGC takes a serious view of any act that may constitute contempt and will not hesitate to take appropriate action to protect the administration of justice.
Nagaenthran K. Dharmalingam was executed in Singapore on 28 April 2022.
The AGC made a statement on 28 April 2022, asserting that Nagaenthran was given a fair trial and had exhausted his rights of appeal and almost every other recourse under the law over some 11 years.
The Central Narcotics Bureau (CNB) made a statement on 28 April 2022, saying that Nagaenthran's actions when committing the crime was a deliberate, purposeful and calculated decision.
The CNB mentioned that Nagaenthran knew what he was doing at the time of the offence, as concluded by the judges in related court findings.
The CNB stated that there were misinformation spread about Nagaenthran's mental state.
Nagaenthran was not intellectually disabled at the time of his offence, according to the CNB.
This was based on Nagaenthran's attempts to evade the authorities and inconsistent accounts of how and what led to him committing the offences.
Many people supported the government's stand on Nagaenthran's case.

Three days before Nagaenthran's execution, Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong and Minister for Foreign Affairs Vivian Balakrishnan responded to their Malaysian counterparts that Nagaenthran was accorded full due process under the law.
Malaysia's foreign minister Saifuddin Abdullah acknowledged Nagaenthran's execution and stated that this issue would not affect the diplomatic ties between Malaysia and Singapore.
The Malaysian foreign minister upheld respect for the sovereignty rights of Singapore to decide on its own judicial system and laws.

Faishal Ibrahim, Singapore's Minister of State for Home Affairs, stated that legislative changes would be made to address the abuse of court processes and impose penalties.
Faishal Ibrahim highlighted the negative effects of drug abuse on individuals and society, using examples of recent attacks in Buangkok Crescent, Queenstown, and a police shooting.
During a June 2022 BBC HARDtalk interview, K Shanmugam, Singapore's Law Minister, defended the death penalty as a means to protect citizens and maintain a safe society.
Shanmugam cited a 2021 WHO report that linked 500,000 deaths to drug abuse in a single year.

Shanmugam compared Singapore's drug arrests in the 1990s, which were around 6,000 people a year, to the current rate of about 3,000 people a year, attributing the decrease to Singapore's strict drug laws.
Shanmugam dismissed concerns about the execution of Nagaenthran, stating that the courts found he was not intellectually disabled and made a calculated decision to bring drugs into Singapore.
Shanmugam quoted a modified version of a well-known quote to emphasize the importance of addressing drug-related fatalities.

Opposition parties in Singapore, including Reform Party, People's Power Party, and Red Dot United, expressed concerns about allegations of a climate of fear among lawyers, potentially discouraging them from representing drug traffickers on death row.

Chief Justice Sundaresh Menon addressed an increasing trend of baseless legal applications made by inmates, specifically mentioning Nagaenthran's case, and called on lawyers not to engage in such procedures.

Violet Netto, a lawyer who represented Nagaenthran in his second-last appeal, was arrested and investigated for practicing without a valid certificate in Nagaenthran's case and the last-ditch appeals of two other death row inmates.

Under Singaporean law, solicitors must apply for a practising certificate for every practice year they act as advocates and solicitors, and Netto's certificate had expired when she represented Nagaenthr
On 10 May 2022, Violet Netto, a lawyer, was arrested and investigated for acting as a lawyer and solicitor without a valid practising certificate on at least three occasions.
Nagaenthran's case was one of the cases in which Netto represented him without a valid certificate.
The other two cases were the last-ditch appeals of death row inmates Pausi Jefridin and Roslan Bakar.
Under the law, solicitors must apply for a practising certificate for every practice year they act in the capacity of an advocate and solicitor.
Netto's certificate was expired at the time she represented Nagaenthran.
If convicted, Netto potentially faced the maximum sentence of six months' jail, a S$2,500 fine, or both.
M Ravi, a human rights lawyer, represented Nagaenthran before Netto.
Ravi was subjected to seven separate professional disciplinary inquiries.
These inquiries may result in Ravi being fined, suspended or struck off the Bar as a lawyer.
Ravi was also given a travel ban which restricted him from going to Malaysia.
Rights groups and Malaysian lawyers criticized Singapore for supposed harassment of lawyers.
They stated that Singapore should respect the criminals' rights to legal representation.
Nagaenthran's mother and another prisoner Datchinamurthy Kataiah found themselves without legal counsel to argue their cases.
On 25 May 2022, the Court of Appeal ruled that Ravi and Netto should pay over S$20,000 in costs to the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) as compensation.
The compensation was for the unnecessary costs incurred by the lawsuits both lawyers made without solid evidence in Nagaenthran's case.
Ravi was to bear 75% of the total cost while the remaining 25% would be covered by Netto.
A small-scale public funding event was carried out to gather funds to help Ravi and Netto to discharge their fine.
